  "document": {
    "metadata": {
      "title": "Complications of bronchoscopy: A concise synopsis",
      "year": 2015,
      "authors": [
        "David L Stahl",
        "Kathleen M Richard",
        "Thomas J Papadimos"
      ],
      "journal": "International Journal of Critical Illness and Injury Science",
      "doi": "10.4103/2229-5151.164995",
      "pmid": ""
    },
    "sections": {
      "abstract": "Flexible and rigid bronchoscopes are used in diagnosis, therapeutics, and palliation. While their use is widespread, effective, and generally safe; there are numerous potential complications that can occur. Mechanical complications of bronchoscopy are primarily related to airway manipulations or bleeding. Systemic complications arise from the procedure itself, medication administration (primarily sedation), or patient comorbidities. Attributable mortality rates remain low at < 0.1% for fiberoptic and rigid bronchoscopy. Here we review the complications (classified as mechanical or systemic) of both rigid and flexible bronchoscopy in hope of making practitioners who are operators of these tools, and those who consult others for interventions, aware of potential problems, and pitfalls in order to enhance patient safety and comfort.",
      "methods": "Narrative review of historical and contemporary literature on complications of flexible (fiberoptic) and rigid bronchoscopy, including questionnaire-based cross-sectional surveys, prospective observational series, and retrospective cohort reviews. No formal meta-analysis was performed.",
      "results": "Reported complication rates for flexible bronchoscopy vary widely by era and study design but are generally low. A 1970s survey of 1,041 physicians reported 12 deaths in 48,000 cases, 52 life‑threatening airway complications (most commonly bronchospasm), and four instances of bronchial brush breakage (at least one requiring thoracotomy). Prospective and retrospective series report low infectious and hemorrhagic events: pneumonia occurred in 2 of 24,521 procedures in one series and in 5 of 908 procedures across 13 hospitals; bleeding occurred in 6 of 908 procedures in one prospective series, and pulmonary hemorrhage >50 mL occurred in 5 of 4,273 procedures in a large academic center; a single unrelated epistaxis event was reported (1 of 4,273). Reported pneumothorax rates range from 0.07-0.16% and respiratory failure from 0.2-0.31% in more recent studies, though absolute counts were not provided. Systemic complications have decreased over time with improved monitoring and sedation practices."
    }
  },
